<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="61" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,601,1057]" pageId="1" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis box="[201,299,925,949]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="61">Remarks</emphasis>
: This new species differs from all the others in the genus in having the penis lacking processes and its stem strongly laterally compressed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="61" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,601,1057]" pageId="1" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis box="[201,321,997,1021]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="61">Etymology</emphasis>
: The specific epithet is derived from the Latin word “ 
<emphasis box="[928,999,997,1021]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="61">calvus</emphasis>
”, referring to the absence of processes on the penis.
</paragraph>
